******
[1] Valparaiso region, Chile
Date: Fri 27 Jan 2017 18:50
Source: Bio Bio Chile [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://bit.ly/2jCjn3f


From 1995 to date there have been 18 cases of hantavirus infections in the Valparaiso region, 14 of which were fatal and 3 of these occurred in the past year [2016] in Quillota province, one fatal; for this the call issued for cleanup and individual precautions.

Due to this, the Subchief of the Health SEREMI [local ministerial administrative unit], Mario Mendez, gave some advice to avoid infection in rural areas while camping or in agricultural activities.

"What we suggest is that before cleaning up outbuildings or houses, ventilate them well, apply bleach and afterward sweep or clean," he indicated.

[Byline: Maximiliano Ortiz, information from Mariel Gonz치lez]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Although not specified in this or previous reports from the region, the hantavirus involved in these cases no doubt is Andes virus. This virus is endemic in Chile, and cases of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome occur every year. Andes virus is rarely transmitted directly person-to-person and this only occurs with very close physical contact, usually within the family.

Images of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligoryzomys_longicaudatus#/media/File:Raton_colilarga.jpg.

Maps of Chile can be seen at http://www.ildado.com/genimg/chile-map5.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4799333,57414. - Mod.TY

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4799333,54750.]

******
[2] Bio Bio region, Chile
Date: Wed 25 Jan 2017
Source: Biobio Chile [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://bit.ly/2kFJdRB


A 45-year-old forest worker is hospitalized in the Las Condes Clinic in the metropolitan region; he is the 3rd confirmed case of [a] hantavirus [infection] in the Bio region. He is progressing well.

The man, a resident of the Santa Barbara community in Bio Bio province, was involved in a camp that was not authorized. This is the place where possibly he was infected by the virus, explained the SEREMI epidemiologist Cecilia Soto.

The work is going on to monitor his family members and contacts in the Quilaco area where they might have been exposed.

With this case there are now 3 cases in the area. One of these is currently in serious but stable condition in the Las Higueras Hospital in Talcahuano. The other case is a 69-year-old man, from the Arauco community, who died from the virus [infection], raising the case fatality rate to 33 percent this year [2017].

As far as the forest fires are concerned, Cecilia Soto stated that there is no direct consequence to the occurrence of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat [the rodent host of Andes virus] in the vicinity because in previous years it has been established that, "displacement [of the rodents] in the vicinity of the affected areas by fires is not more than 200-300 meters [556-984 ft] from the perimeter of the damaged area."

The official also signaled that the accumulation of garbage and trash permits the presence of colonies of long-tailed pygmy rice rats; cleanup of urban and peri-urban areas is the responsibility of the municipality.

Bear in mind that hantavirus [infections cause] is an acute respiratory disease that can rapidly lead to death. Thus, it is important in springtime to take precautions to avoid the infection.

[Byline: Claudia Mi침o, information from Cristi치n Valdebenito]

