******
[3] El Bolson, Rio Negro province, Argentina
Date: Wed 25 Jan 2017
Source: ElPat치gonico [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.elpatagonico.com/hay-dos-casos-sospechosos-hantavirus-esquel-n1533362


There are 2 suspected cases of hantavirus [infections] admitted to the Esquel hospital and it was stated that their samples have been sent to the Malbran Institute in Buenos Aires and are in process for confirmation. Results will come in a few days.

"The risk that we face is for the populace that lives in the area and for tourists; because of this we always recommend that if they decide to camp, they choose clean areas where safe areas for visitors are offered" said Radio el Chubut.

As for the suspected cases, Biondo states that they are patients from the Andean region and are under observation due to their seriousness as indicated by their clinical picture. Although not confirmed, "they are suspected cases that are compatible with the disease."

This information about a hantavirus [infection] case came to light after El Patagonico published its Tuesday edition. The case is a 27-year-old woman who is hospitalized with a reserved prognosis in Esquel after having contracted the disease in El Bolson, Rio Negro while on vacation.

The specialist recalled that in 2012, there was a massive bloom of colihue cane, so that [preventive] measures applied were even more extreme because of the presence of great numbers of rodents due to the food source from the seeds provided by this plant species. "This is not an alarming situation, rather a usual endemic situation and the idea is to prevent [infections] and not alarm people," he said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This area is in the Andean area where Andes virus is endemic in the long-tailed pygmy rice rat. Rat populations increase when the colihue cane booms and sets seeds.

A map of Argentina and Chile can be seen at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4799333,5827. - Mod.TY]
